  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Using the complex <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math> -model as a prototype for a system which is simulated by a worm algorithm, we show that not only the charged correlator <math altimg="si15.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">〈</mo><msup><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>⁎</mo></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">〉</mo></math> , but also more general correlators such as <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">〈</mo><mo stretchy="false">|</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">|</mo><mo stretchy="false">|</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">|</mo><mo stretchy="false">〉</mo></math> or <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">〈</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">arg</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">arg</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">〉</mo></math> , as well as condensates like <math altimg="si5.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">〈</mo><mo stretchy="false">|</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy="false">|</mo><mo stretchy="false">〉</mo></math> , can be measured at every step of the Monte Carlo evolution of the worm instead of on closed-worm configurations only. The method generalizes straightforwardly to other systems simulated by worms, such as spin or sigma models.</subfield>
